    "answer_id" : 6698444,
    "question_id" : 6698354,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 3.0",
    "body" : "<p>The <a href=\"http://code.google.com/p/guava-libraries/\" rel=\"noreferrer\">Google Guava</a> library (which I'd highly recommend anyway, if you're doing work in Java) has a <a href=\"https://google.github.io/guava/releases/20.0/api/docs/com/google/common/base/Charsets.html\" rel=\"noreferrer\"><code>Charsets</code></a> class with static fields like <code>Charsets.UTF_8</code>, <code>Charsets.UTF_16</code>, etc.</p>\n\n<p>Since Java 7 you should just use <code>java.nio.charset.StandardCharsets</code> instead for comparable constants.</p>\n\n<p>Note that these constants aren't strings, they're actual <code>Charset</code> instances. All standard APIs that take a charset name also have an overload that take a <code>Charset</code> object which you should use instead.</p>\n"
  }, {
